Translation (English)
Planned Energy Retrofit Concept
1. Building envelope (insulation)
The basement ceiling, attic, and windows are to be fully upgraded for energy efficiency.
The façade is not in optimal condition, but exterior insulation may be difficult because—as you know—it is a terraced/row house.
→ Internal insulation could be an option.
→ If scaffolding will be erected for the roof renewal anyway, it should be examined whether exterior insulation (e.g., ETICS/WDVS or a ventilated façade) would then be economically and energetically sensible.

2. Energy generation & heating
Photovoltaic system (approx. 5.8 kWp on the south-facing roof) with battery storage → I think this is fundamentally a solid measure.

Now it gets a little more experimental:
Two buffer/storage tanks (one for heating/cooling, one for domestic hot water; can be interconnected in winter).
The idea is to use two storage tanks that are hydraulically coupled in winter to act together as a central heat store for space heating and domestic hot water—supplied by a wood stove with back-boiler, a domestic hot-water heat pump, and possibly an electric immersion heater.

In summer the tanks should be operated separately:

The smaller tank is used for DHW and is heated by PV surplus (via heat pump and/or immersion heater).

The larger tank serves as a cold store for passive cooling via the underfloor heating; the heat pump is operated at night to lower the tank temperature.

A heat exchanger probably also makes sense to keep DHW hygienically separated and to enable flexible, efficient use of both tanks.

Domestic hot-water heat pump (DHW-HP) for hot water (possible locations: basement with outside air supply, plant room/utility room, outdoors?)
Wood stove with back-boiler in the living room to support heating in winter
Water-based underfloor heating throughout the living area (likely quite a lot of work? Possibly combine with insulation work)
Immersion heater in the buffer tank for PV surplus utilization (probably not necessary or sensible; more of an emergency measure)

Control
Possibly Home Assistant or an open-source solution, including:

Automatic prioritization of self-consumption

Control of immersion-heater use with PV surplus

Switching storage operation between summer/winter modes

Notifications when wood stove support is useful

3. Summer cooling
Night operation of the heat pump to cool a separate tank (temperature control to avoid condensation)

Possibly passive cooling via underfloor heating

Automated switching between heating and cooling mode

Funding ideas
Federal funding for efficient buildings – individual measures (BEG EM, BAFA)
15–20% grant for individual measures such as:

Insulation of basement ceiling, top floor ceiling, possibly exterior walls

Replacement/installation of new windows and doors

Installation of a heat pump (including DHW heat pump)

Installation of a heat store or hydraulic optimization
Requirements: energy-efficiency expert for application & confirmation
Combinable with low-interest loans from KfW

KfW program 261 (loan + repayment grant)
Alternative to BAFA grant: e.g., up to €60,000 per housing unit as a loan
Possible when achieving an Efficiency House standard (e.g., EH 85 or better)
More relevant for comprehensive retrofits (including façade)

Photovoltaics & storage
VAT waived for installations from 2023 (0% VAT)
Regional battery storage funding? (L-Bank, local utilities)?
Feed-in tariff under the EEG?

L-Bank Baden-Württemberg (supplementary funding)?
Combinable with BEG/KfW?
Low-interest loans and repayment grants for energy-saving measures

Technical evaluation (precise & practical)
0) Quick diagnostics from your data
Heated floor area: 113 m²; 2023 space-heating use: 9,824 kWh ⇒ ~87 kWh/m²·yr (good for a 1970s row house; room for improvement).

DHW volume: 16.86 m³ ≈ ~881 kWh/yr thermal (ΔT≈45 K).

Electricity: 2,671 kWh/yr (3 occupants) = typical-low.

Implication: Envelope upgrades (roof, basement ceiling, windows, targeted thermal bridge fixes) plus ventilation hygiene can likely cut space-heating energy by ~25–40% (order of magnitude) without radical façade work.

1) What’s strong in your concept
PV + battery on a south roof is robust. A 5.8 kWp array in BW typically yields ~5.5–6.3 MWh/yr; pairing with 7–10 kWh storage materially raises self-consumption and resilience.

Envelope first (basement ceiling, attic, windows) is the most cost-effective way to reduce heat load and enable low flow temperatures—key for heat-pump efficiency and for any cooling via hydronics.

Controls (self-consumption logic, seasonal modes) are essential; your plan to orchestrate sources/sinks is on point.

2) Elements that need re-thinking (to avoid cost/complexity traps)
A. Two-tank strategy + DHW heat pump + wood-boiler
Complexity & losses: Two tanks, seasonal coupling, immersion backup, DHW-HP, wood back-boiler, UFH cooling, and control logic is a lot. Each extra component adds standby losses, failure modes, and commissioning overhead.

Redundancy risk: If you later add a proper air-to-water heat pump (AWHP) for space heating/cooling, a separate DHW-HP becomes redundant.

Operational friction: Relying on a wood stove to “charge” heating buffers is inconvenient, weather-dependent, and can overheat tanks without a well-engineered heat-dump and safety hydraulics.

Improvement:
Prefer one stratified combi buffer with a fresh-water station (FriWa) for DHW (plate heat exchanger + pump, legionella-safe, no stored potable hot water) or a dedicated DHW cylinder with internal HX, both driven by a single AWHP that is reversible for cooling. Keep a small immersion heater as a true emergency/anti-legionella fallback. Add the wood stove (if desired) as a comfort/backup heat source, not a primary.

B. Cooling via underfloor heating
Condensation risk: UFH supply must stay ≥18–20 °C and be dew-point-controlled (humidity sensors in reference rooms + surface sensors on manifolds). UFH only removes sensible heat; it does not dehumidify.

Comfort limitation: Cooling capacity is modest (often 10–25 W/m²) in retrofits. Expect gentle background cooling, not AC-like performance.

Improvement:

Use a reversible AWHP with dew-point control and consider adding one or two small fan-coil units in key zones to handle peak loads and latent moisture via condensate removal.

If you keep a separate “cold tank,” ensure it’s really needed; in many cases direct HP→UFH/fan-coil with proper controls is more efficient and simpler.

C. DHW heat pump placement & efficiency
DHW-HPs that pull air from indoors can cool and dehumidify the space (sometimes nice in a basement), but in winter COP drops if drawing cold outside air through ducts.

If you adopt an AWHP for space heat, integrate DHW with the same machine—one compressor, one outdoor unit.

3) Building-physics risk areas & fixes (very important)
Open staircase: Strong stack effect increases uncontrolled ventilation losses.
Fix: Add an airtight door or glazed partition at basement or ground-floor level; combine with good basement-ceiling insulation.

Loggia / interior balcony (thermal bridge):
Risk: Significant linear thermal bridge → cold interior surfaces → condensation/mold.
Fix options:

Enclose as winter garden with high-performance glazing; or

Targeted internal insulation with capillary-active boards (calcium silicate or wood fibre) and meticulous detailing at junctions. Cutting a structural thermal bridge with an Isokorb-type element is gold standard but invasive in retrofit.

Open, covered entrance below living space:
Fix: Best is to enclose to a vestibule (Windfang); at minimum, insulate the ceiling below + address side-wall junctions.

Internal insulation caveat:
Use vapour-open, capillary-active systems (e.g., CaSi) to buffer moisture and avoid interstitial condensation. Avoid mixed layers that create a vapour trap. Get details modeled (e.g., Glaser/WUFI).

Ventilation:
After tightening the envelope, plan ventilation. Decentralized or small MVHR with summer bypass improves IAQ, reduces mold risk, and aids summer comfort.

4) Underfloor heating retrofit realism
1970s slabs often have limited height. UFH may require floor buildup, door adjustments, and acoustic detailing.
Alternatives:

Wall heating in select rooms (great at low temperatures)

Low-temperature radiators (fan-assisted convectors) in rooms where UFH is impractical.
Any emitter strategy should target 30–35 °C design flow temps at −7 °C outside to keep HP COP high.

5) Controls & hydraulics (what “good” looks like)
One reversible AWHP, weather-compensated, with outdoor unit sized to your design heat load (likely ~5–8 kW after envelope measures; confirm via heat-loss calc, not rules of thumb).

Stratified combi buffer sized ~20–30 l per kW of HP as a starting point (fine-tune by manufacturer guidance).

FriWa for DHW or dedicated cylinder with HX; schedule anti-legionella if needed.

PV orchestration: Only enable immersion heater when battery SoC ≥ X%, predicted PV > load, and DHW/buffer below setpoint.

Cooling safety: Dew-point logic (room RH + temp) with hard limits at manifold.

Hydraulic balancing and mixing circuits as needed; log temps/flows; keep a simple fallback mode.

6) PV & battery sizing notes
On a south roof, maximize array within shading/roof constraints—the BOS cost per extra kWp is low.

Battery: 7–10 kWh typically balances evening/night use; oversizing raises cycling losses and cost without much extra benefit.

Prioritize load shifting (DHW midday, washers/dryers, EV) before adding more battery.

7) Regulatory & practical
Winter garden and enclosing the entrance typically require permits and façade coordination (fire, drainage, appearance).

District heating contract runs to end-2028; verify early-termination clauses and any return-to-grid obligations for de-installation of substation (if any).

Funding: The BEG/KfW landscape changes; verify current rules before committing and route applications via an Energy-Efficiency Expert (EEE).

8) Prioritized, lower-risk plan (phased)
Envelope & airtightness

Basement ceiling, attic, window upgrade; fix the open staircase (door/partition).

Address the worst thermal bridges (loggia, entrance).

Plan ventilation (decentralized or compact MVHR).

PV first, maximize feasible array, then battery ~7–10 kWh.

Emitter strategy

UFH where practical; wall heating or low-temp radiators elsewhere. Target low flow temps.

Heating & DHW

Install one reversible air-to-water HP sized from a proper EN 12831 heat-loss calc.

Use one combi buffer + FriWa (or DHW cylinder). Keep immersion heater as emergency only.

Keep the wood stove with back-boiler only as a comfort/backup source (with a heat-dump and certified safety kit).

Cooling

Enable reversible HP cooling with dew-point control; consider 1–2 fan-coil units for peaks/latent.

Controls & monitoring

Implement PV-aware scheduling and clear seasonal modes. Log temps, RH, SoC, COP.

Funding & compliance

Engage an EEE early; stage applications; align scope with current BEG/KfW and any L-Bank options.

9) Common pitfalls to avoid
Designing around a DHW heat pump + wood back-boiler and only later adding an AWHP → ends up redundant and more expensive.

UFH cooling without dew-point control → condensation and floor damage.

Internal insulation without capillary-active materials/details → mold risk.

Over-segmenting storage (two large tanks) → higher standby losses, complexity.

Skipping ventilation after tightening the envelope.

10) Rough impact expectations (order-of-magnitude)
Envelope + thermal-bridge fixes: ~25–40% less space-heating energy vs. current ~9.8 MWh/yr.

PV 5.8 kWp: ~5.5–6.3 MWh/yr generation; with battery and HP load shifting, self-consumption commonly 50–70% achievable.

Reversible AWHP vs. resistance/immersion: 3–4× less electricity per kWh of heat (seasonal).

UFH cooling: mild background cooling; expect to add fan-coil(s) if you want crisp summer comfort.

Bottom line
Keep the spirit of your plan (PV-centric, smart control, seasonal flexibility) but simplify the plant: one reversible AWHP + one well-designed buffer + FriWa, envelope first, targeted thermal-bridge fixes, and ventilation. Treat the wood stove as comfort/backup. That gives you the best efficiency-to-complexity ratio, lower risk, and an easier path to commissioning and living with the system day-to-day.

