ChatGPT said:

Thought for 29s
Short answer: yes—your dual-buffer concept can work well and give you exactly the comfort + independence you want, if it’s engineered with the right safeguards and simplified where it counts. Below is a precise “yes-if” blueprint and the traps to avoid.

Will it work?
Yes, if you (1) use a reversible air-to-water heat pump for space heat/cool, (2) keep DHW hygienically separated, (3) protect against condensation and stove overheat, and (4) control stratification and standby losses.
A DHW-only heat-pump (Brauchwasser-WP) cannot chill a space-cooling buffer—so plan a reversible AWHP (L/W) for the heating/cooling loop. The wood stove with back-boiler is fine if you like firing it; just treat it as a comfort/backup source with proper safety hydraulics.

Recommended architecture (keeps your two buffers)
Sources

Reversible air-to-water heat pump (AWHP) (primary source for heating + cooling).

Wood stove with water jacket into the heating buffer (comfort/backup).

PV-driven immersion allowed but only as a last-priority dump.

(Optional) Keep a small DHW-HP only if you really want DHW independent of the AWHP; otherwise the AWHP should also do DHW.

Stores (two-tank)

Heating/Cooling Buffer (stratified, well insulated, 600–1000 L typical):

Connected to emitters (UFH / low-temp radiators / a few fan-coils).

Receives heat from AWHP + stove; receives “cold” from AWHP in summer nights.

Hydraulic separator/low-loss header role to protect AWHP and pumps.

DHW Tank or Combi buffer + Fresh-Water Station (FriWa):

Hygienic separation via plate HX (FriWa) or internal coil; no potable storage if you prefer legionella-safe on-demand.

Priority charging at midday from PV via AWHP; immersion only when battery SoC high and setpoints not met.

Hydraulic notes

Consider glycol in the outdoor HP circuit and a plate HX to the house side; keeps stove + UFH loop water clean and oxygen-free.

Install anti-condensation loading valve (e.g., Laddomat) on the stove loop to keep return > ~60 °C (prevents tar/condensation).

Provide a thermal discharge safety valve + heat dump for the stove (solid-fuel safety per EN 303-5), and adequate expansion vessel sizing.

Controls (safety first, smarts second)

Hard-wired safety controls on HP, stove, pumps, and temperature limits.

Dew-point control for cooling (see below).

Home Assistant/Open-source only for orchestration (PV logic, schedule, notifications)—not for safety interlocks.

Comfort realism (with numbers)
Cooling via UFH

Typical UFH cooling capacity in retrofits: ~10–25 W/m² (dew-point limited).

For 113 m² that’s roughly 1.1–2.8 kW sensible cooling—pleasant background cooling, not “AC cold.”

Add 1–2 small fan-coil units in key rooms to cover peaks and remove latent moisture (UFH cannot dehumidify).

Cold-buffer usefulness

Example: 500 L cooled from 20 → 10 °C stores ~5.8 kWh of “cold.”

At a 2 kW load it bridges ~3 h peak. Good for peak shaving + night pre-cool.

Heating buffer

1000 L with ΔT = 20 K stores ~23 kWh. With a 3 kW heat load that’s ~7–8 h autonomy (nice for PV windows, wood firing, and anti-cycling).

Bottom line: the buffers support your independence goals (shift energy in time), but they don’t replace proper emitter sizing and dew-point-safe control.

What to watch out for (critical)
Use a reversible AWHP for the space loop

A DHW-only HP cannot charge a cold buffer for UFH cooling.

Size AWHP from an EN 12831 heat-loss calc (post-insulation); many houses like yours land around ~5–8 kW design load.

Dew-point & condensation management

Mandatory: indoor RH + temp sensors per reference zone and a hard limit on manifold supply (typically ≥ 18–20 °C).

Fan-coils recommended for peak + latent loads (with condensate drain).

Thermal-bridge remediation (loggia, open entrance, staircase)

Enclose the entrance (wind-fang) or at least insulate its “ceiling.”

Loggia: winter-garden conversion or capillary-active internal insulation; detail junctions carefully.

Add an airtight door/partition at the basement stair to tame stack effect.

Legionella hygiene

Prefer FriWa (on-demand DHW via plate HX) so you don’t store potable hot water.

If you store DHW: maintain ≥ 55 °C or run periodic pasteurization.

Wood stove safety & usability

Install loading valve, thermal discharge valve, heat-dump radiator, and ensure gravity circulation/fail-safe on power loss.

Coordinate early with the Bezirksschornsteinfeger (emissions, chimney sizing, BImSchV).

Standby losses & stratification

Large stores must be class-leading insulated (≥ 100 mm PU equivalent, high-quality jacket, insulated fittings).

Keep piping short & insulated; use baffles/diffusers to preserve stratification.

Two tanks = more surface area → more losses; compensate with insulation and smart operating temps.

Emitters for low temperatures

Aim for 30–35 °C flow at design winter to keep COP high. Where UFH is hard, use wall heating or low-temp radiators (fan-assisted convectors are compact and effective).

Ventilation after tightening the envelope

Add decentralized MVHR or a compact unit (with summer bypass). It improves IAQ, reduces mold risk, and helps summer comfort.

Control strategy for independence

Priority stack: PV → battery → DHW (midday) → heating buffer; immersion only when SoC high and setpoints unmet.

Cooling: night-charge the cold buffer with the AWHP; daytime UFH/fan-coil cooling with dew-point control.

“Still not good?” — When the two-buffer plan is a no
If you are unwilling to add dew-point controls (and, ideally, one or two fan-coils), UFH-only cooling can be disappointing or risky.

If you prefer minimal maintenance/complexity, a single combi buffer + FriWa driven by one AWHP is simpler and almost always more efficient in real life.

If space is tight for two well-insulated tanks, consider a single larger combi and do the “cold-charge at night” directly without a separate cold tank.

Commissioning checklist (what to ask your pros for)
EN 12831 heat-loss + summer cooling load calculation.

Hydraulic schematic with safety devices (stove) and dew-point logic documented.

Sensor plan (temps, RH, flow, pressure) and data logging for first season.

Functional test scripts: winter mode, summer mode, stove charge, PV surplus, anti-legionella, power-failure behavior.

Insulation schedule for pipes/fittings and measured standby loss targets.

Verdict
If you like firing the stove and want the time-shifting comfort of hot/cold buffers, keep the two-tank idea—but do it with a reversible AWHP, hygienic DHW separation, dew-point-safe cooling, and top-tier insulation/stratification. That preserves your independence goals while keeping efficiency and risk under control.

