We can do few point controls, fan coils and so on


So fresh hot water, how do we do it. On demand.
Heat exchanger?
ChatGPT said:

Thought for 32s
Short answer: yes—on-demand “fresh hot water” = a Fresh-Water Station (FriWa): a plate heat exchanger + primary-side variable-speed pump + controller and sensors. It heats mains water instantly using heat from your hot buffer (charged by the heat pump / stove / PV). No potable hot water is stored ⇒ very low legionella risk and excellent PV-timing control.

Below is a clean, buildable spec.

How it works (in practice)
Primary side (closed loop): from your heating buffer’s hot top (e.g., 50–60 °C) through a plate heat exchanger (PHE), back to the buffer.

Secondary side (potable): mains cold → PHE → (optional anti-scald mixing valve) → DHW taps.

Control: Outlet DHW sensor (and often cold-in sensor). The controller modulates the primary pump to keep DHW at setpoint (e.g., 45 °C).

Hygiene: No stored potable DHW. Optionally schedule weekly 60 °C “top-of-buffer” for extra safety.

Two good topologies with your two-buffer plan
A) One large heating/cooling buffer + FriWa (simplest)

Keep the buffer stratified: top kept ~55–60 °C when PV is strong (midday), lower zones at 30–40 °C for space heating.

FriWa draws from the hot top. Immersion heater only as last-priority PV dump.

B) Separate small “DHW charge buffer” + big heating/cooling buffer

Small tank (e.g., 150–300 L) maintained at ~55–60 °C feeds the FriWa; big tank stays low-temp for COP/cooling.

Pros: excellent stratification and minimal mixing penalties. Cons: more surface area ⇒ insulate very well.

Sizing the FriWa (what “good” looks like)
Use: 
