Select an ECM pump that can do this flow at the PHE’s pressure drop (the controller will modulate it).

Heat-pump + buffers reality
Your AWHP doesn’t need 25–35 kW; the buffer supplies the peak. The HP recharges the buffer after draws (ideally at midday with PV).

Keep top-of-buffer hot only when needed (PV window) to protect COP; otherwise let it sit lower.

Key components (bill of materials)
FriWa module (stainless PHE, primary ECM pump with PWM/0–10 V, controller, sensors).

Thermostatic anti-scald mixing valve set ~45–48 °C (safety).

Dirt separator / magnetic filter on primary; Y-strainer on potable inlet; isolation valves + service ports for descaling.

Water softening if hardness ≳ 10–12 °dH to reduce PHE scaling.

High-grade insulation on all primary pipework and the tank jackets (≥ 100 mm PU equiv.).

Check valves to prevent thermosiphon.

Optional DHW recirculation: Prefer on-demand/button or motion-triggered recirc to minimize losses; continuous 50–55 °C recirc is hygienic but increases standby losses markedly.

Controls & setpoints (practical)
DHW setpoint: 45 °C at taps (mixing valve).

Buffer top setpoint: 55–60 °C during PV hours; lower outside those windows.

Anti-legionella: Weekly top-of-buffer to 60 °C (HP high-temp mode or short electric boost).

Priorities: PV → battery → DHW charge (midday) → space heat. Immersion only with high SoC and unmet setpoints.

Logging: DHW outlet temp, primary flow/ΔT, buffer stratification temps.

Fan-coils & cooling (since you’re adding them)
Keep dew-point control in cooling mode (room RH + supply limit).

Use fan-coils for latent removal; UFH stays for gentle sensible cooling and background comfort.

When to pick a DHW cylinder instead
Very long DHW runs with mandatory continuous recirculation (e.g., multi-bath home where instant hot water everywhere is a must). A coil cylinder at 55–60 °C can be simpler.

Otherwise, the FriWa wins on hygiene, PV timing, and summer flexibility.

Bottom line
Yes—on-demand DHW via a FriWa (plate heat exchanger) is the right match for your two-buffer concept. Size the station ~25–35 kW, keep a hot top zone (or small DHW buffer) for it, add anti-scald mixing, softening if needed, service ports for descaling, and orchestrate charging to midday PV. That gives you hygienic, responsive hot water without compromising your comfort or independence goals.

