ChatGPT said:

Thought for 18s
Absolutely—here are two “day-in-the-life” runbooks for your system with two buffers, reversible air-to-water heat pump (AWHP), FriWa (fresh-water station) for on-demand DHW, UFH, and a couple of fan-coils. I’ll use realistic numbers so you can picture flows and controls; adjust after your heat-loss/cooling-load calc.

Scenario A — Cold winter day (e.g., −5 °C outside, target 21 °C inside)
Assumptions

AWHP sized from EN 12831, ~6–8 kW at A−7/W35 (space heat).

Buffer #1 “HC-buffer” (heating/cooling): ~800 L, stratified, very well insulated.

DHW via FriWa (plate HX) drawing from hot top of HC-buffer; anti-scald mixing to 45–48 °C.

Emitters: UFH base (design flow ~30–35 °C), + 1–2 fan-coils (optional/rarely used in winter).

PV 5.8 kWp, battery ~10 kWh.

06:00–09:00 — Morning peak (showers + warm-up)
DHW on demand (FriWa): Two showers @ 8 L/min each → FriWa draws ~25–30 kW instantaneously from the hot top (55–60 °C).

Control: FriWa modulates the primary pump to hold 45 °C at taps; anti-scald mixing smooths spikes.

Buffer: Hot top cools a few kelvin; stratification remains intact.

Space heating: AWHP runs weather-compensated to keep mid-buffer ~35–40 °C; UFH circuits mix down to ~30–33 °C supply.

COP (ballpark): ~2.5–3.0 at A−5/W35.

Battery: Covers part of morning house load; AWHP draws from grid + battery as orchestrated.

09:00–12:00 — Steady space heat
AWHP runs steadily (anti-cycling via buffer), holding HC-buffer mid-zone ~35–40 °C, top drifting back toward 55 °C if there’s headroom.

Wood stove (optional): If you light it, the loading valve keeps return ≥ 60 °C, sending 70–80 °C water into the upper buffer coil/port.

Effect: AWHP reduces output/pauses; stove carries part of the load.

Safety: Thermal-discharge valve + heat-dump radiator armed in case of power loss/overheat.

12:00–15:00 — PV midday window
PV priority logic:

Top up battery to target SoC.

Raise buffer top to 58–60 °C (short AWHP run at higher setpoint).

If surplus remains, brief immersion heater enable (strict cap; last priority).

DHW “readiness”: With top at 58–60 °C, FriWa can serve multiple draws later without forcing the AWHP to high temps when it’s cold outside.

17:00–22:00 — Evening comfort
Space heat: UFH holds 21 °C. If you run the stove, it charges the top of buffer; AWHP idles or trims.

DHW: Kitchen use handled on-demand via FriWa; hot top setpoint maintained if PV/battery allow.

Battery: Discharges to cover evening household load.

22:00–06:00 — Night
Setback: Slight indoor setpoint reduction (e.g., 0.5–1 K) if you like.

AWHP: Low, steady output to cover the building’s base losses; avoids cycling.

Anti-legionella: Weekly, schedule a midday 60 °C top-of-buffer pasteurization (use PV), not at night.

What’s happening behind the scenes

Stratification: Diffusers/baffles maintain a hot top (DHW), warm middle (space heat), cooler bottom.

Hydraulics: HC-buffer acts as low-loss header; pumps are ECM with ΔP control; all pipes and fittings heavily insulated.

Safety: Wood loop has loading valve, gravity path, thermal-discharge valve; AWHP has its built-ins; Home Assistant does orchestration, not safety interlocks.

Edge cases

Very cold snap: AWHP shifts to slightly higher flow temps (still aim ≤ 40–45 °C). Stove contribution is valuable here.

Grid outage: AWHP stops; stove goes to gravity heat-dump, house coasts on buffer + emitters.

Scenario B — Hot summer day (e.g., 33–35 °C outside, target 24–25 °C inside)
Assumptions

Same plant; reversible AWHP in cooling mode.

Dew-point control enabled (indoor sensors for T/RH).

UFH provides gentle sensible cooling; fan-coils handle peaks + latent (dehumidify via condensate drain).

Cold-top strategy: We use the same HC-buffer; charge a cold zone at night.

00:00–06:00 — Night pre-cool (coolest ambient, best EER)
Cooling charge: AWHP runs in cooling to bring lower buffer zone to ~12–16 °C.

EER (ballpark): ~3–4 at night conditions.

Controls: Stop charge when predicted dew point + margin would be exceeded at UFH/fan-coil supply.

06:00–12:00 — Morning comfort, low power
UFH cooling: Supply limited by dew point (e.g., if indoor 26 °C, 50 % RH ⇒ dew point ≈ 15 °C → supply ≥ 17–18 °C).

Expect ~10–20 W/m² sensible cooling—pleasant, steady background.

Fan-coils: Run at low fan to trim indoor temp and remove latent moisture (condensate to drain).

AWHP: Mostly idle, house cools from cold buffer.

12:00–14:00 — PV window + DHW production
DHW charge: AWHP briefly switches to heating mode to raise top of buffer to 55–60 °C for FriWa (or charges a small dedicated DHW buffer if you chose that variant).

This is scheduled to PV generation to avoid grid draw.

Cooling during DHW: UFH/fan-coils continue using remaining cold in the lower buffer; if needed, the switch is timed (e.g., 30–45 min) and then AWHP returns to cooling.

14:00–20:00 — Afternoon peak
Cooling top-up: If indoor T/RH rise and PV is strong, AWHP resumes cooling to re-charge the cold zone (still dew-point-limited).

Fan-coils: Take the lead in hottest hours; UFH stays as gentle background.

20:00–24:00 — Evening
Comfort maintenance: As outdoor cools, loads drop; AWHP cycles less.

Ventilation: MVHR summer bypass or night flush if outside becomes cooler/drier than inside.

What’s happening behind the scenes

Dew-point governor: Real-time dew-point calculation from indoor T/RH; manifold supply clamped (e.g., ≥ 18–20 °C).

Priority rules: PV → battery → short DHW charge → cooling top-up (if RH safe). Immersion heater stays off unless SoC very high and setpoints unmet.

Hydraulics: Same buffer, but “reversed” stratification in cooling hours (cooler bottom). Diffusers prevent mixing; all cold lines condensation-insulated.

Edge cases

Very humid day (high latent load): UFH feels weak; fan-coils do most of the work to dehumidify.

Simultaneous big DHW draw: FriWa uses the hot top; AWHP may briefly prioritize reheating the top (preferably during PV high). Cooling resumes after.

Quick “what we use / how it works / what happens” (at a glance)
Sources: Reversible AWHP (heat/cool), wood stove with back-boiler (optional winter), PV + battery, immersion (last resort).

Stores: One large HC-buffer (hot top for winter/DHW; cold bottom for summer), optionally a small dedicated DHW charge buffer.

DHW: FriWa (plate HX) gives on-demand hot water from buffer top (legionella-safe; anti-scald mixed to 45–48 °C).

Sinks (emitters): UFH (low-temp heat; dew-point-limited cooling) + fan-coils (peaks & dehumidification).

Controls: Weather curve (heating), dew-point (cooling), PV-aware scheduling, strict safety interlocks (hardware), Home Assistant for orchestration and notifications.

What happens: Winter—AWHP and/or stove keep a hot top for DHW and a warm mid-zone for UFH. Summer—night pre-cool the buffer, use UFH + fan-coils by day; short PV-timed DHW heat burst at midday.

If you want, I can turn this into a commissioning checklist for your installer (sensors, setpoints, and functional tests) so they can wire it exactly like this.

