ChatGPT said:

Thought for 29s
Awesome—since you’re okay with fan-coils, dew-point controls, and two buffers, here are four precise “runbooks” that include thermal + electrical behavior. I assume:

PV: ~5.8 kWp, hybrid inverter with islanding/backup output and an Essential Loads sub-panel.

Battery: ~10 kWh usable.

Plant: Reversible AWHP (space heat/cool), HC-buffer (~600–1000 L) + FriWa (on-demand DHW), wood stove w/ back-boiler (loading valve + heat-dump + thermal discharge safety), UFH + 2 fan-coils.

Envelope upgrades as discussed (basement/attic/windows, key thermal bridges mitigated).

If you don’t have a hybrid inverter/essential sub-panel, I note the differences under each outage scenario.

1) Cold winter day, snowy — sustained grid outage (no warning)
Conditions
Outdoors: −5 °C, snow on PV modules (initial PV ≈ 0 until you clear panels).

Building demand after retrofit: ~2.5–4.0 kW (order-of-magnitude; depends on wind/sun).

Buffer energy (example): 1000 L × 4.18 kJ/kgK × ΔT 20 K ≈ 23 kWh usable.

What happens (with hybrid inverter + Essential Loads)
t = 0–30 min

Grid drops → island mode. AWHP stops (high draw); controls & pumps stay up via battery.

Space heat switches to buffer-only. You light the stove (if not already running).

Load shedding auto-applies: non-essentials off; circulators, controls, a few lights, fridge stay on.

t = 0–4 h

UFH/fan-coil pumps (≈ 30–60 W each) + controls (~10–20 W) draw < 200 W baseline.

Stove begins supplying 4–8 kW thermal (typical). Loading valve holds return ≥ 60 °C; buffer top warms; UFH mixes to ~30–35 °C supply.

Battery life at 200 W ≈ 10 kWh / 0.2 kW ≈ 50 h (before DHW/fans). Plenty of autonomy for pumps/controls.

DHW during outage

FriWa needs its pump (~60–120 W) only during draws.

Plan short, staggered showers (low-flow heads 6–8 L/min). Buffer top must be ≥ 55–60 °C (stove helps).

Avoid long recirculation loops (or run button-triggered recirc only).

PV recovery

Clear snow on 1–2 strings if safe; you might get 0.3–2 kW even in winter sun → slows battery decline, can run FriWa/AWHP briefly at midday for DHW if desired.

Thermal safety

If power flickers: your thermal discharge valve + heat-dump protect the stove loop.

Keep at least one radiator/heat-dump on gravity circuit open.

If you don’t have islanding/Essential Loads
All pumps off → UFH can’t circulate; only gravity flow on stove loop to heat-dump.

Use room-sealed stove for direct radiant/convective heat in occupied rooms; keep doors closed to zone the house.

DHW: no FriWa (pumpless), boil water or use camp shower contingency.

Practical tips
Pre-label breaker map: “Essential Loads sub-panel” must include stove circ., buffer pumps, FriWa pump, controls, networking, fridge, a few outlets/lights.

Keep snow rake for PV; keep dry kindling.

Pre-set low-power Home Assistant mode: no heavy automations during islanding.

2) Winter → Summer transition (≈ 1 week)
Goal
Stop overheating, keep comfort cheap. Shoulder seasons often swing 5–15 K day–night.

Day-by-day logic (tunable)
Days 1–2 (still chilly nights)

Heating curve −10–15 %, UFH supply cap 28–30 °C.

Night setback −0.5 to −1 K; morning pre-heat only if indoor < setpoint.

DHW via FriWa at midday PV; buffer top 55–58 °C only 60–90 min/day.

Days 3–5 (mild days)

Heating OFF from ~10:00–18:00; free solar gains allowed.

MVHR summer bypass on warm afternoons; night flush windows if outdoor < indoor.

Enable dew-point sensing; trial fan-coils on low for late afternoons.

Days 6–7 (first warm spell)

Switch AWHP to standby cooling with dew-point clamp (UFH ≥ 18–20 °C supply).

Cold-charge buffer bottom a bit pre-dawn (cheap kWh / lower ambient), then ride passive cooling + low fan-coil in afternoon.

Things to watch
Short-cycling: use buffer to keep AWHP in longer on-cycles (min runtime ≥ 10 min).

Dew-point: indoor 24 °C @ 55 % RH → dp ≈ 14.6 °C → keep UFH supply ≥ 16–17 °C once cooling starts in earnest.

Pollen/IAQ: consider higher MVHR filtration as windows open.

3) Summer → Winter transition (≈ 1 week)
Goal
Bring heating online smoothly, restore DHW high-temp routine, verify the stove/hydraulics.

Days 1–2

Cooling off, dew-point control stays armed for any warm spike.

Night pre-heat disabled; morning UFH warm-up if indoor < 21 °C.

Days 3–4

Weather-comp curve enabled (start gentle: 0.2–0.3 K/°C slope, design ~35 °C flow at −5 °C).

DHW midday again; top-of-buffer 55–60 °C for 60–90 min on PV.

Days 5–7

Boiler-stove test (first fire): verify loading valve opens, return ≥ 60 °C, check thermal discharge valve trip test, inspect expansion vessel pre-charge.

Hydraulic balance UFH loops after first cool nights; confirm room-by-room delta-Ts.

Things to watch
Noise/vibration on first heating runs (air in circuits).

Condensate from any last fan-coil cooling (clear drain).

Legionella routine re-enabled weekly (prefer midday PV).

4) Hot summer, sustained grid outage (no warning)
Conditions
Outdoor 33–35 °C; indoor target 25 °C; RH may be 50–65 %.

PV available (good irradiance), but only useful with islanding.

Cooling loads: 2–4 kW sensible on hot afternoons for a 113 m² row house with improved envelope; latent significant on humid days.

With islanding/Essential Loads
t = 0–2 h

AWHP drops out at first, then returns in cooling if PV allows (you choose a PV-tracking mode).

Strategy: Daytime → run fan-coils on low/med and AWHP cooling only when PV ≥ demand. Night → fans only, no compressor.

Power budget (typical)

2× fan-coils low: 40–120 W total

UFH circ. (if used for mild cooling): 30–60 W

Controls/network: 15–25 W

AWHP cooling: 0.6–1.8 kW electrical (depending on capacity/EER)

Midday PV window (11:00–16:00)

On clear days, 2–4 kW DC available even with sub-optimal angle/heat.

Run fan-coils steadily; let AWHP pre-cool buffer bottom to ~14–16 °C.

DHW: choose HP-based DHW charge (efficient) vs immersion (simple) only if PV surplus is obvious. Keep FriWa demand clustered after DHW charge.

Evening/night

Battery is precious: reserve for pumps/controls + a single fan-coil on low if needed (say 100 W → ~100 h theoretical, but add fridge etc.).

Night flush if outdoor becomes cooler/drier than indoor.

Without islanding
No AWHP, no fans. Lean on passive measures: blinds/awnings fully closed, internal doors closed, night cross-ventilation, ceiling/USB fans on power banks if available.

DHW: FriWa pumpless, so kettle/solar shower fallback or wait for grid.

Moisture control (key in hot outages)
If fans can run: fan-coils remove latent moisture (condensate), improving comfort more than temperature alone.

Without fans: avoid bringing in humid air until dew point outdoors < indoor.

Electrical & control notes that make all of this work
Hybrid inverter with islanding + Essential Loads sub-panel (critically: UFH/fan-coil circulators, FriWa pump, plant controller, stove circ., networking, fridge, select outlets).

Automatic load shedding:

Tier-1 (always on in islanding): controls, pumps, fridge.

Tier-2 (daytime PV only): fan-coils, AWHP cooling/heating bursts, washer.

Tier-3 (only high SoC + strong PV): immersion heater, EV at low amps.

PV snow plan: roof-safe rake; clear at least one string first.

Outage playbooks in the controller (scenes): Winter-Outage and Summer-Outage buttons set all the right setpoints, priorities, and notifications in one go.

Data you log: buffer top/mid/bottom, room T/RH, manifold supply/return, pump states, battery SoC, PV power. Helps you tune day-2 of any event.

Quick “sanity” numbers (order-of-magnitude)
Buffer (1000 L, ΔT 20 K): ~23 kWh thermal (≈ 7–10 h of 2.5–3.5 kW load without sources).

Cold buffer (500 L, 20→12 °C): ~5.8 kWh “cold” (≈ 2–4 h of 1.5–2.5 kW sensible cooling).

Battery (10 kWh) at 200 W pumps/controls: ~50 h autonomy; add a single 100 W fan-coil → ~33 h; add 1 kW AWHP → not sustainable at night, daytime PV only.

Bottom line
Your two-buffer architecture handles transitions gracefully and is resilient in outages—if you wire the right circuits to backup, keep dew-point control for cooling, and train the system with simple scenes for each scenario.

For winter outages, the stove + buffers + tiny electric load is a strong combo.

For summer outages, comfort hinges on fan-coils + PV daytime operation; don’t expect 24/7 compressor cooling—use PV windows and thermal mass.

