Let's do another scenario.

Cold winter day, aim for least grid energy used 
ChatGPT said:

Thought for 54s
Great—here’s a precise, low-import “day plan” for a cold winter day using your two-buffer setup (reversible AWHP, FriWa, UFH + a couple fan-coils, PV ~5.8 kWp, battery ~10 kWh, wood stove w/ back-boiler). I’ll give (1) the control strategy by time-of-day and (2) a compact energy budget for sunny vs overcast variants so you can see where grid kWh still sneak in.

Objective
Minimize grid import without sacrificing basic comfort or DHW hygiene.

Core principles
PV hours = do “expensive” things (heat DHW, recharge buffer with HP, top up battery).

Non-PV hours = live off buffer + stove + battery; keep HP off.

Never use immersion except as a last-resort PV dump with high SoC.

Zone + schedule to reduce peak demand: low setpoint in unused rooms, short DHW draws clustered after midday DHW charging.

Hour-by-hour runbook (example setpoints—tune after heat-loss calc)
05:30–09:00 (pre-sunrise → morning)
AWHP: OFF.

Space heat: UFH supplied from buffer (target manifold 30–33 °C).

DHW: Avoid if possible; if needed, FriWa serves from hot top of buffer (55–58 °C) without calling the HP.

Stove: Optional: Light a small morning fire if living area dips < 20.5 °C.

Battery: Runs controls + circulators (~150–200 W baseline).

Ventilation: MVHR normal/low.

09:00–11:00 (PV rising)
Forecast check: If sun expected, delay HP until ≥ 0.8–1.0 kW PV available.

Stove: If cloudy/cold, start a sustained burn now (best thermal bang for least grid).

HP: Still OFF unless PV is clearly above house load.

11:00–14:00 (PV peak window)
Priority order:

Charge battery to target SoC (e.g., 90–100 %).

Heat DHW: run HP to lift buffer top to 55–60 °C for FriWa (60–90 min).

Space-heat recharge: keep mid-buffer ~35–40 °C using HP only while PV ≥ HP draw.

Stove: Reduce/skip during strong PV; save logs for evening.

Loads: Run any flexible loads now (wash, dishwasher, etc.).

14:00–17:00 (PV taper)
HP: Wind down; OFF if PV < HP draw.

Stove: If the forecast says cold evening/night, start a controlled burn to raise buffer top/mid; keep return ≥ 60 °C via loading valve.

DHW: Cluster showers after midday top-of-buffer charge where possible.

17:00–22:00 (evening)
HP: OFF.

Space heat: UFH from buffer + stove supplies. Aim living area 20.5–21.0 °C, bedrooms 19–20 °C (close doors, thick curtains).

Battery: Covers residential + pumps.

Ventilation: Normal/low; short boost only for humidity/odors.

22:00–05:30 (night)
AWHP: OFF.

Stove: Final small reload if needed; otherwise coast on buffer.

Setback: −0.5…−1.0 K as tolerated.

Battery: Reserve for controls/pumps/fridge; keep other loads minimal.

Energy budget (order-of-magnitude; tune with your real data)
Thermal stores (for intuition):

1000 L buffer, ΔT = 20 K ≈ 23.2 kWh heat.

Wood stove back-boiler: ~5–7 kW to water while burning; a 5 h burn supplies 25–35 kWh thermal (plus ~2 kW room radiant/convective).

Electrical baselines:

Pumps + controls: ~150–200 W when running → 3.6–4.8 kWh/day.

House non-HVAC loads (fridge, lights, IT, etc.): ~200–300 W avg → 4.8–7.2 kWh/day.

Battery usable: ~10 kWh (assumed).

Case A — Sunny winter day
PV yield (mid-winter, clear): ~6–9 kWh.

HP runs only under PV: Use 4–7 kWh electric for HP (COP ~2.8–3.2 at W35) → ~12–22 kWh thermal into buffer/DHW.

Stove: One 3–4 h burn → 15–25 kWh thermal.

Thermal sum covers typical cold-day space heat + DHW (varies, but ~35–55 kWh).

Battery: PV tops to ~100 %; evening/night house + pumps mostly off-grid.

Expected grid import: ≈ 0–2 kWh (small gaps, inverter overheads, clouds passing).

Case B — Overcast/snow day
PV: 0–2 kWh (clear panels if safe; otherwise assume near-zero).

HP: Keep OFF (poor COP + grid draw); rely on stove + buffer.

Stove: 6–7 h sustained burn → 30–45 kWh thermal.

Battery: Carries pumps + house for most of the day (≈ 9–12 kWh demand).

Expected grid import: ≈ 0–3 kWh (if battery can’t fully cover night/peaks).

Tip: Pre-charge battery to 100 % on the preceding sunny day if the forecast shows a gray spell.

Control & setpoint cheatsheet (min-grid mode)
HP enable rule: Only ON when PV power ≥ HP electrical draw and buffer mid/top below target. Otherwise OFF.

DHW: FriWa target 45–48 °C at taps; buffer top only to 55–60 °C during PV hours.

Space heating: Weather curve tuned for W35 design; aim manifold 30–33 °C most of the day.

Zones: Living 20.5–21 °C; bedrooms 19–20 °C; close doors; use thick curtains at dusk.

Ventilation: MVHR normal/low; avoid long boost cycles.

Immersion heater: Disabled (enable only as PV dump at high SoC with strict cap).

Stove safety: Loading valve (ret ≥ 60 °C), thermal discharge valve + heat-dump, gravity path confirmed.

Battery priority: Keep pumps/controls/fridge on Essential Loads; defer EV/oven/etc. to sunny windows.

What typically breaks the plan (and how to fix)
Morning showers before DHW charge → high buffer drain → HP must run off-PV.

Fix: Shift showers to early afternoon or after midday DHW heat.

HP allowed to chase setpoint under clouds → grid spikes.

Fix: Hard “PV-coupled” HP rule with a minimum PV threshold and hysteresis.

Thermal bridges & air leakage inflate load.

Fix: Keep the stairwell partitioned, entrance insulated/enclosed, loggia mitigated; these save more kWh than any control tweak.

Bottom line
On sunny winter days you can run near-zero import by: PV-coupling the HP, charging DHW + mid-buffer at midday, using the stove strategically, and letting battery handle night baseloads. On gray days, keep the HP off, lean on stove + buffer, and use the battery to ride through lights/pumps—grid import then stays in the 0–3 kWh range.

You said:
Okay so who would I get/contact to make this detailed plan or rework for me?
ChatGPT said:

Thought for 28s
Great question. For a project this integrated (two buffers, reversible heat pump, FriWa, UFH + fan-coils, PV+battery, islanding, ventilation, thermal-bridge fixes), you’ll want a TGA/HVAC design lead + an EEE (Energie-Effizienz-Experte), with the installers and specialists working under them.

Below is a practical, Baden-Württemberg-ready playbook: who to contact, who leads, what to demand, and how to tender—so you end up with a buildable, fundable plan.

Who to contact (roles you actually need)
TGA Fachplaner (HLS/GA) – independent HVAC/BMS engineer

Leads the technical concept and detailed hydraulics (R&I), sizing, setpoints, control strategy, dew-point logic, commissioning plan.

Familiar with VDI 4645 (heat pumps), EN 12831-1 (heat loss), VDI 2078 (cooling load), DIN EN 1264 (UFH), VDI 2035 (water quality), VDI 6023/DVGW W551 (DHW hygiene), DIN EN 12828 (safety/expansion), DIN 1946-6 (ventilation).

EEE – Energie-Effizienz-Experte (dena-Liste)

Mandatory for BEG/KfW subsidies and quality assurance.

Verifies building-physics, thermal bridges (DIN 4108 Beiblatt 2), and documentation.

Coordinates funding applications (BAFA/BEG EM; KfW 261 if relevant).

SHK-Meisterbetrieb (Ausführung) – heating/cooling installer

Experienced with reversible AWHP + buffer(s) + FriWa + cooling and hydraulic balancing (Verfahren B).

Provides brands, execution details, and aftercare. Ask for similar references.

Elektro-Fachbetrieb + PV/Hybrid-Speicher-Partner

Designs hybrid inverter + essential-loads sub-panel, VDE-AR-N 4105 compliance, battery sizing, ATS/islanding behavior, and Home-Assistant/KNX gateways.

Bezirksschornsteinfeger

Approves wood stove with back-boiler (BImSchV), chimney sizing, safety (thermal discharge valve, gravity heat-dump).

Bauphysik/Architekt/Statiker (as needed)

For winter garden / enclosing entrance, loggia conversion, permits, structural thermal-bridge breaks (e.g., Isokorb), and façade/window works.

Lüftungsbauer

For DIN 1946-6 ventilation concept (decentral MVHR or compact unit) once the envelope is tightened.

Who should lead (two good setups)
Option A (recommended): TGA Fachplaner leads the technical design; EEE co-leads funding & QA. Installers execute against the TGA spec.

Option B (design-build): A strong SHK firm with in-house planning delivers design + build, but you still engage an external EEE for subsidies and checks.

Exactly what to demand (deliverables/specs)
Ask the TGA/EEE team to produce a single coordinated package with:

Calculations & concepts

EN 12831-1 room-by-room heat-loss calc (post-insulation).

VDI 2078 cooling-load calc + dew-point limits & setpoint strategy.

DIN 1946-6 ventilation concept.

Thermal-bridge assessment (DIN 4108 Beiblatt 2); WUFI as needed for internal insulation.

Emitter concept (UFH/wall heating/low-temp rads) targeting flow 30–35 °C at design winter.

Buffer sizing with usable kWh (hot/cold), stratification hardware (diffusers/baffles), standby loss targets (W).

FriWa sizing (≥25–35 kW instantaneous at 10→45 °C), anti-scald mixing, water treatment (VDI 2035), service ports.

AWHP selection (reversible), source/sink temperatures, glycol/HX decision, expansion vessel and safety valves (DIN EN 12828).

Wood stove hydraulics: loading valve (ret ≥ 60 °C), thermal discharge valve, gravity heat-dump, power-fail behavior.

Controls: weather curve, dew-point governor (sensors + limits), PV-coupled priorities, emergency modes; which interlocks are hard-wired.

Schematics & schedules

R&I (P&ID) hydraulics (all valves, pumps, sensors, safeties), control I/O list, alarm points.

Electrical SLD: hybrid inverter, battery, Essential-Loads sub-panel (exact circuits), metering (SoC, PV, house), network.

BoM with model numbers, pipe sizes, insulation thicknesses (≥ 100 mm PU-eq for tanks; cold lines anti-condensation), and commissioning spares.

Commissioning & QA

Step-by-step commissioning scripts (winter mode, summer mode, PV-charge, DHW boost, stove charging, outage scenes).

Hydraulic balancing plan (valve presets/flows), data-logging points (buffer top/mid/bot, RH/T, ΔT, SoC, flows).

Handover docs + homeowner cheat sheets (including Outage-Winter and Outage-Summer scenes).

Funding set

EEE-ready BEG/KfW forms, photos, invoices, and conformity statements.

How to vet candidates (fast)
Ask for two references with reversible AWHP + buffer + FriWa + cooling (not just heating-only HPs).

Request a sample R&I and commissioning protocol from a past job.

Ask which brands they prefer for FriWa, pumps, and HPs—and why (spares, local service).

Confirm they will implement dew-point control (room RH sensors + manifold supply clamp) and hard-wired safeties (not just software).

Ensure the electrician has done hybrid inverter + essential-loads panels with islanding before.

How to source them (where to look)
EEE: dena “Energie-Effizienz-Expertenliste” (filter for Wohngebäude + BEG EM, region BW).

TGA/HVAC designers: search “TGA Fachplanung HLS GA” in Stuttgart/Reutlingen/ES region; ask architects for recommendations.

Installers: SHK-Innungsbetriebe with HP + cooling references; PV firms that explicitly offer hybrid/backup systems.

Schornsteinfeger: your local Bezirksschornsteinfeger for early feasibility on the stove/back-boiler.

Tender strategy (keep it clean)
Commission TGA/EEE for LPH 1–3 (concept) → you get the calcs, R&I, and SOW.

Tender LPH 5–8 (execution) to ≥3 SHK firms and ≥2 electrical/PV firms using the same package.

Require as-built drawings and measured balancing as a condition of final payment.

Short inquiry template (German)
Betreff: Anfrage TGA-Planung + EEE-Begleitung – Wärmepumpe (heizen/kühlen), Zwei-Puffer, FriWa, PV/Notstrom

