What can I get from kfw? Credit wise and "förderung" wise? Or are other Förderungen better?
ChatGPT said:

Thought for 5m 39s
Absolutely, Luke — here’s the up-to-date, no-nonsense view of what you can get from KfW (credits + grants) and how that plays with BAFA and local options. I’ll also flag what’s realistically best for your specific plan (row house, 1972, PV + heat pump + storage + UFH + smart control).

1) Direct grants (“Zuschuss”) you can get
A. Heating replacement: KfW Zuschuss 458 – “Heizungsförderung”
What it funds: New heat pump (incl. DHW heat pump if part of the heating system), planning, installation, storage tank(s), distribution upgrades, etc.

Grant rate:

Base 30%

Efficiency bonus +5% for heat pumps with natural refrigerant (e.g., R290) or ground/water source

Climate speed bonus +20% only when replacing oil/coal/gas/night-storage/old biomass (≥20 years). Replacing district heating does not qualify for this bonus.

Income bonus +30% if taxable household income ≤ €40k.

Absolute cap: 70% max of eligible costs, and eligible costs for a 1- or 2-family home are capped at €30,000 → so the maximum grant is €21,000.

Implication for you: If you switch from Fernwärme to an R290 air-to-water HP, expect 35% (30%+5%) on eligible costs (cap €30k → max ~€10,500). If you ever replaced an old gas/oil unit you’d hit 55% (base+efficiency+speed) up to €16,500. 
kfw.de
+1
bafa.de

B. Building envelope & non-heating systems: BAFA – BEG Einzelmaßnahmen (EM)
Building envelope (basement ceiling, roof, windows, possibly façade): 15% base + 5% iSFP-Bonus (needs a valid iSFP). Cost cap: €30,000/WE/year, €60,000 with iSFP.

Anlagentechnik (außer Heizung) such as ventilation with heat recovery and “Efficiency Smart Home” (MSR/automation): same 15% + 5% iSFP, same caps.

Notes: Caps are per residential unit per calendar year. You need an EEE to confirm. 
bafa.de
+1

C. DHW heat pump, buffers, distribution, etc. (fit with your “dual buffer” concept)
BEG explicitly lists “Einbau hocheffizienter Warmwasser-Wärmepumpen”, Wärmespeicher (incl. ice/latent), and Wärmeverteilung/Wärmeübergabe (UFH, hydraulic balancing, etc.) as eligible associated measures in the heating track. In practice you include these with KfW 458 if they’re part of the heating project; some distribution/optimization items can also be funded under BAFA Heizungsoptimierung. 
bafa.de
+1

D. Planning & site supervision (“Fachplanung & Baubegleitung”)
50% grant on eligible costs, capped at €5,000 for 1-/2-family homes (per application/calendar year). This is separate and stacks with the above. 
bafa.de

E. PV & storage (tax + EEG)
0% VAT on PV and batteries since 1 Jan 2023 (reduces upfront cost directly).

EEG feed-in tariff still applies; current small-system rates are around ~8 ct/kWh (Teileinspeisung) and ~12–13 ct/kWh (Volleinspeisung) depending on the commissioning window. Not a grant, but relevant to economics. 
Bundesministerium der Finanzen
bundesnetzagentur.de

2) Low-interest loans (KfW “Kredit”)
A. KfW 358/359 “Einzelmaßnahmen Ergänzungskredit”
Up to €120,000 per dwelling as a loan in addition to your already approved KfW 458 and/or BAFA EM grant(s).

Extra interest reduction if household income ≤ €90k (Program 358 “Plus”). Good to bridge large capex while keeping grants. 
kfw.de
+1

B. KfW 261 “Wohngebäude – Kredit” (Effizienzhaus)
For comprehensive refurb to an Efficiency House (EH85 or better). Up to €150,000/WE, repayment subsidy 5–45% depending on EH level (+bonus for “Worst Performing Building” and serial renovation).

This is attractive only if you aim for a certified EH level (likely requires façade insulation + airtightness + ventilation). For a 1972 row house with façade constraints, EH85 might be achievable but expect significant scope. You cannot “double-fund” the same measure in 261 and BAFA EM. 
kfw.de

C. KfW 270 “Erneuerbare Energien – Standard” (PV + battery financing)
Optional PV/battery loan; open to private persons. Pure financing (no grant). Compare rates vs. your house bank. 
kfw.de
+1

3) Regional add-ons (Baden-Württemberg / Nürtingen)
City of Nürtingen: the PV/battery municipal program ended (only plug-in/balcony PV still supported).

L-Bank BW: mainly loans (e.g., Wohnen mit Zukunft: Photovoltaik) rather than grants for private owners; earlier battery grants are no longer active. Use if the loan terms beat your bank. 
klimaschutz-nuertingen.de
l-bank.de

4) What’s likely “best” for your project (precision, stacking, reality)
Heating system (your dual-buffer + AWHP + UFH + controls):
Apply via KfW 458; specify R290 AWHP to secure the +5% efficiency bonus. Because you’re replacing district heat, assume ~35% grant on eligible costs (cap €30k → max ~€10,500). Add BAFA Heizungsoptimierung items if they don’t fit into 458. 
kfw.de
bafa.de
+1

Envelope (basement ceiling, roof, windows; façade if feasible):
BAFA EM at 15% (or 20% with iSFP) with €30k/€60k eligible-cost caps → material savings on your largest efficiency levers. 
bafa.de

Ventilation + Smart control:
BAFA EM 15–20% (“Anlagentechnik außer Heizung”, “Efficiency Smart Home”). 
bafa.de

EEE planning & supervision:
Budget it and take 50% grant up to €5k. 
bafa.de

Funding mix:
Pair grants (KfW 458 + BAFA EM + Baubegleitung) with KfW 358/359 loan to smooth cash flow. Consider KfW 270 only if PV financing rates beat your bank. 
kfw.de

If you pursue a full EH standard:
Switch to KfW 261 instead of BAFA EM for those measures, but only if your EEE confirms that EH85 (or better) is achievable with your façade/loggia/entrance constraints at sensible cost. 
kfw.de

5) Rough grant arithmetic (illustrative)
Envelope €35k eligible → €5.3–7.0k grant (15–20%).

Heating package (HP + buffers + DHW-HP + distribution): if €35–45k eligible, KfW 458 grant is capped by €30k eligible → at 35% ≈ €10.5k max.

Ventilation/control €10k → €1.5–2.0k.

Baubegleitung €8–10k fees → €4–5k grant.
Total ballpark (without climate-speed bonus): ~€21–24k in grants, plus optional KfW 358/359 loan.

6) Practical next steps (to maximize funding, avoid pitfalls)
Ask your EEE (Michael Keil) to finalize/refresh the iSFP → unlock the +5% iSFP on BAFA EM and help decide whether an EH-route (KfW 261) is realistic.

Sequence applications correctly: apply before signing trades (except with suspensive clause). Don’t mix 261 and EM on the same measure. 
bafa.de

Choose an R290 AWHP (or ground/water if feasible) to capture the +5% efficiency bonus under KfW 458. 
kfw.de

Include associated measures (buffers, UFH, hydraulic balancing) under the heating project where possible; use BAFA Heizungsoptimierung for remaining distribution upgrades. 
bafa.de
+1

PV: leverage 0% VAT; compare KfW 270 vs. bank terms; set EEG metering correctly. 
Bundesministerium der Finanzen
kfw.de

Local check: Nürtingen battery/PV grant is discontinued, so don’t rely on municipal subsidies (besides balcony PV). 
klimaschutz-nuertingen.de

If you want, I can turn this into a one-pager you can send to your EEE and installers with the exact grant/loan mix per measure and a checklist of documents (BzA/TPB, offers, declarations, etc.).

