ChatGPT said:

Thought for 1m 8s
Got it. You want to get reliable power into a separate garage (one building in between) so you can charge an electric car—ideally using your own solar production and keeping grid use low. Here’s a clear, engineering-grade rundown of what actually works, the trade-offs, and how to execute.

The four viable paths (ranked by technical and economic sense)
1) Direct supply from your house to the garage (preferred, if routing is feasible)
Idea: Lay a dedicated three-phase cable from your main distribution board to the garage and install a controllable wall charger there. This keeps one metering point, so your solar and battery control can do genuine “surplus charging”.

What you need (in addition to the wall charger):

A buried, armoured five-core copper cable in conduit (for example NYY-J 5×6…5×16 mm² depending on distance and charging power).

Own three-pole circuit breaker (16 A for eleven kilowatt, 32 A for twenty-two kilowatt).

Residual-current protection: either a Type B device in the sub-distribution or a Type A plus a wall charger with certified six milliampere direct-current detection (most good wall chargers have that built in).

Surge protection in the main board (recommended) and correct earthing and bonding.

A small communication line or robust network connection to the wall charger (Ethernet is best).

Civil works: trench at about sixty centimetres depth on private land, sand bed, warning tape; horizontal drilling if you must cross paved areas or a public path.

Voltage-drop sizing (engineering rule-of-thumb):
Target ≤ 3 percent drop at full load. For three-phase copper at four hundred volts:

Eleven kilowatt (sixteen ampere per phase):
– up to ~60 m: 5×4 mm² is usually fine
– ~60–120 m: 5×6 mm²
– ~120–200 m: 5×10 mm²

Twenty-two kilowatt (thirty-two ampere per phase):
– up to ~30 m: 5×6 mm²
– ~30–60 m: 5×10 mm²
– ~60–100 m: 5×16 mm²

(These are conservative; your electrician will calc precisely with installation method, temperature, and cos phi.)

Costs (very rough, because routing dominates):

Electrical hardware + wall charger + protection: ~1 800–3 500 Euro

Cable + conduit: ~6–15 Euro per metre (cross-section dependent)

Civil works private soil: ~50–120 Euro per metre

Paved areas / drilling: ~150–400 Euro per metre

Crossing a public road can add several thousand Euro just for permits and drilling
Total typical: ~2 500–12 000 Euro if it’s all on private ground; 10 000–30 000 Euro if you must cross public space.

Legal/coordination: If any part crosses someone else’s parcel or common property, you need a written easement. Public land needs municipal permits.

Why this is best: One metering point → your solar, battery, and control can truly minimize grid import at the garage.

2) New, separate grid connection for the garage (works when a cable run is impossible)
Idea: Apply for a separate meter and service at the garage, then install the wall charger there.

Pros: No long private cable, straightforward technically.
Cons: Your house solar cannot directly offset the garage consumption because it’s a different metering point. You’ll pay a basic meter fee. Surplus charging based on your house meter is not possible; you can only “time-shift” charging to sunny hours (still helpful, but not the same).

Costs (very rough):
Network operator connection fee (site-dependent) + internal wiring + wall charger → often 2 500–6 000 Euro on simple sites, more if civil works are needed.

Use when: Routing a private cable is blocked by legal or civil-works cost.

3) Solar on the garage roof (with grid at the garage)
Idea: Put a small photovoltaic system on the garage roof and a wall charger under the same meter.

Pros: Local solar helps charging on sunny days even if the garage is metered separately.
Cons: Limited roof area; separate metering still isolates this from your house battery and house loads; paperwork and structural checks needed.

Use when: You have (or must create) a separate grid connection at the garage and a decent garage roof.

4) Off-grid solar + battery at the garage (not recommended as a primary solution)
Idea: Panels and a big battery in the garage, no grid.
Reality check: To add, say, 20 kilowattstunden on a summer day you’d need several kilowatt peak and a substantial battery. Costs and complexity outweigh the benefit unless you only need occasional top-ups.

How to decide (fast decision tree)
Can you get a private cable route approved end-to-end?
Yes → choose Option 1.
No → go to 2.

Is a new grid connection at the garage feasible?
Yes → choose Option 2, optionally add Option 3 later.
No → only Option 4 remains (rarely economical).

Making Option 1 work perfectly with “solar-first” charging
Hardware checklist (added to your house system):

Wall charger that can accept a live current setpoint from your controller (local network API is ideal).

A bidirectional energy meter at the house feed-in point (so the controller knows instant import/export in real time).

Optional sub-meter on the wall charger circuit (for precise logging and safety limits).

Reliable network to the charger (Ethernet preferred).

Dynamic load management so you never exceed the main fuse rating (charger reduces current when the house is cooking, heat pump defrosts, etc.).

How the control works (no code):

The controller (for example your home automation) reads solar output, house consumption, battery state, grid import/export every second.

It sets the charging current so that grid import remains near zero (for example clamp at ±100 watt).

If the house battery has a minimum reserve target (for outages), the controller honours that before ramping the car.

When the sun fades, the charger ramps down smoothly; at night it pauses unless you’ve scheduled a cheap-tariff window.

Numbers to aim for:

Minimum charging current per phase is typically six ampere (about 4.1 kilowatt at three phases). Some chargers allow single-phase low-power modes for tiny surplus, but check compatibility with the car.

Keep a 3 percent voltage-drop design target on the feeder to the garage.

Design the wall charger for eleven kilowatt unless you really need twenty-two; eleven kilowatt is friendlier to long runs, main fuses, and voltage drop.

If you must choose Option 2 (separate meter at garage)
You can still:

Charge during sunny hours to reduce net grid draw overall (helps your household carbon balance, even if meters are separate).

Use schedule control and dynamic price signals to minimize cost (if you have a flexible tariff).

Add a small photovoltaic system on the garage roof to feed the garage meter directly.

But: your house battery cannot buffer the garage unless both are on the same metering point.

Practical next steps (in order)
Measure and map the straight-line and practical cable routes with lengths and obstacles.

Property and permits check: who owns what? Do you need an easement or municipal permit?

Choose target power (eleven or twenty-two kilowatt). Eleven is enough for almost all daily use.

Main fuse check in the house (many homes have three times sixty ampere; confirm). Plan dynamic load management regardless.

Voltage-drop sizing and protection with your electrician; select cable cross-section from the table above.

Wall charger selection: must support live current setpoint over local network and have compliant direct-current fault detection (either integrated or paired correctly with residual-current protection).

Networking to the garage (Ethernet if possible; otherwise very robust Wi-Fi with dedicated access point).

Civils: trench plan, depth, backfill, any drilling; coordinate dates with neighbours if needed.

Commissioning: test residual-current device, insulation resistance, loop impedance, earth resistance; log a full-power charge and verify voltage drop stays within plan; test surplus-charging behaviour on a sunny day.

Documentation: single-line diagram, protection settings, cable data, test protocols, photos of trench and warning tape before backfill.

Short answer to “can I use my house solar in the garage?”
Yes, cleanly, if the garage is supplied from your house’s main meter (Option 1).

If the garage has its own meter (Option 2), your house solar cannot directly offset that meter; you can still time charging for sunny hours, or add solar on the garage meter.

If you give me the approximate cable distance and whether you want eleven or twenty-two kilowatt, I’ll size the recommended cross-section, list the exact protection devices, and sketch a one-line diagram you can hand straight to the electrician.

