Thought for 29s
That’s workable. If your neighbour is open to it, a private feeder from your house to the garage is the best way to get true “solar-first” charging. Here’s exactly how to approach it—legal + technical—so it’s robust, safe, and neighbour-friendly.

1) Legal/permission path (Germany)
Goal: you want the right to lay, operate, and service a private power cable across your neighbour’s land.

Two levels (pick at least one):

Simple permission (“Gestattungsvertrag”) – a signed agreement between you and the neighbour covering route, reinstatement, and liability.
Pros: quick, cheap. Con: not binding for future owners.

Registered easement (“Grunddienstbarkeit – Leitungsrecht”) via notary + land registry.
Pros: survives ownership changes. Con: takes a few weeks and costs (often low-four-hundreds to ~€1,500 incl. fees, very case-dependent).

What to include (either option):

Exact route plan (to-scale sketch with distances to fixed points).

Depth & build details (buried, in conduit, marker tape; you restore lawn/paving like-for-like).

Access rights (you may open the trench again for repairs; with notice; emergency clause).

Liability & insurance (you carry construction and operating liability).

Cost & compensation (you pay all costs; optionally a one-time goodwill payment, or: you lay an extra empty conduit for their future use).

End of life (you remove or de-energise on request if replaced or house sold, unless easement remains).

Tip: Open with a friendly letter, then go straight to a short one-pager agreement. If they’re positive, consider the registered easement so it’s future-proof.

2) Technical concept (so your electrician can quote fast)
Target power: 11 kW three-phase (more than enough for daily use, gentler on voltage drop and main fuses).
Feeder type: buried five-core copper in protective conduit, from your main board to the garage sub-board.

Cable sizing (rule-of-thumb, 3 % voltage-drop target):

Distance up to ~60 m → 5×4 mm² is usually fine for 11 kW.

~60–120 m → 5×6 mm².

~120–200 m → 5×10 mm².
(Your electrician will calc precisely with installation method and ambient temperature.)

Protection & boards:

In your main board: dedicated three-pole breaker (typically C16 A for 11 kW) feeding the garage submain, plus surge protection if not present.

RCD concept: either a Type B in the sub-board or a Type A combined with a wallbox that has certified 6 mA DC detection (common).

In the garage: small sub-board (RCD + MCB for the wallbox; spare ways for light/outlets).

Dynamic load management: wallbox or controller must be able to dial charging current down when the house load peaks (so you never blow the main fuse).

Data & control (for solar-first):

Ethernet to the garage if possible (or robust Wi-Fi with a dedicated access point).

Bidirectional energy meter at the house grid point (so your controller sees instant import/export).

Optional sub-meter on the EV circuit for precise logging.

Trench & installation basics (typical good practice):

Route on private ground; avoid tree roots.

Depth ~60 cm, sand bed, smooth protective conduit (HDPE), pull rope, and marker tape above.

Gentle bends (respect minimum bend radius); no sharp edges; seal entry points; label both ends.

Restore surfaces like-for-like (paving patterns, turf, gravel).

As-built sketch with photos before backfill (you’ll thank yourself later).

3) Neighbour approach (practical script)
Why: “I’d like to power my garage for EV charging from my own house so I can use my solar and keep grid use low. That means a buried cable crossing your garden along the fence line.”

Assurances: “We’ll trench neatly (≈ 60 cm deep), lay the cable in conduit with marker tape, and restore everything like-for-like. I cover all costs and hold liability.”

Sweeteners: “I can lay an extra empty conduit for you (data/power later), and we can agree a small one-time compensation if you like.”

Paperwork: “Happy to sign a short permission, or we can register a formal easement so it’s binding for future owners.”

Plan: show a one-page route sketch and proposed dates; keep it simple and professional.

4) Alternatives if the route is blocked
Separate meter at the garage: technically easy, but your house solar can’t directly offset that meter; you can still schedule charging for sunny hours.

Small solar on the garage roof: helps daytime charging on a separate meter.

No-dig crossing (HDD/micro-tunnel) for paved sections: costlier but neat when surfaces must stay intact.

5) What I’d prep next (so you can act fast)
Measure the rough distance and note obstacles.

Decide target power (11 kW recommended).

I’ll draft you a one-page route plan (to-scale sketch + trench spec) and a one-page neighbour permission checklist (bullet clauses you can use).

With neighbour’s “yes”, your electrician prices the feeder (cable, conduit, boards, RCD/MCB, wallbox, load management) and a landscaper quotes reinstatement.

If you tell me the approximate metres and where the trench would run (fence line? paved path?), I’ll size the recommended cross-section, list the exact protection devices (breaker/RCD/SPD), and write the two one-pagers you can take to your neighbour and electrician.

